column2: On-study note; Week # 1

Patient presented for Week 1 of treatment with M7824. Patient has been deem eligible for protocol 18-C-0056, she was consented; and will receive her Week #1 treatment today.  Eligibility checklist reviewed by Dr. Houssein Abdul Sater; calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance  is 110 ml/min,  based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine.  Dr. Cappell performed the physical exam and reconciled home medications, her findings are documented in the patient progress note.    Dr. Abdul Sater discussed  the possible side effects of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  He discussed symptom management; including calling treatment team to report side effects immediately at onset.  Research nurse provided her with her study calendar of visits and the important phone numbers to contact her treatment team.  Research nurse reviewed patent's medical history/symptoms, and current medications; which are documented in her first registration note from the initial screening visit.  She has stopped taking all herbal medications as discussed at screening visit in preparation for starting the clinical trial.  Patient does have a Titanium portacath, can receive the M7824 via her port.  Baseline Review/Findings: Depression, mood changes related to diagnosis, since 2017.  Patient states she has taken Lexapro since October 2018.  She started CBD and THC Oil in March 2017 after she received prescription authorization.  She reports decreased to poor appetite since initial diagnosis and post chemotherapy in 2017, for which she uses the CBD Oil.  She takes the THC Oil to help with sleep; she reports episodes of insomnia, also since initial diagnosis in 2017.  She does report her fatigue level varies, sometimes affecting her ADL's.  She takes Calcium and Vitamin D supplements for bone health, since December 2017.
Authored: Protocol Note

column1: Last Updated: 06/12/2019 16:15 by Francis, Deneise C (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,5/28/19,CC-CRIS,

column2: Treatment note; Week #3

Patient presented for Week 3 of treatment with M7824, required labs were collected.  Dr. Leger reconciled all home medication, performed the physical exam, and assessed for adverse events.  His findings are documented in the patient's progress note.    Dr. Abdul Sater met with patient, reviewed her labs, and reviewed her reported adverse events.  Patient reported having mild, throat itching during the infusion on week #1.  She did not report it because it was mild and intermittent.  Once home, she noticed a dry, intermittent cough on the same night.  The throat itching and dry cough, both intermittent lasted for about a week, then resolved by day 7.  She took no interventions for throat and cough.  One day 2 she noticed a red rash to her mid chest area; the rash was self-limiting and resolved by day 3, without intervention.  She reports no other side effects other than those noted.  Dr. Abdul Sater reinforced that she should have reported these events to the infusion nurse and the research team.  Patient verbalized understanding.  Dr. Abdul Sater discussed her results, which are within normal limits, with abnormalities not clinically significant. Based on her current status he has approved week #3 dose of M7824.  He has ordered additional premedications for the M7824; and the drug will be infused over 2 hours today, with reinforcement for patient to report if she has any issues during the infusion.  Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week #5 clinic and visit.  Adverse events reviewed with Dr. Abdul Sater and Dr. Strauss

column2: Treatment note; Week # 7

Patient presented accompanied by her husband and children for week #7 of treatment with M7824, restaging scans and required labs were completed.  Dr. Skorupan reconciled all home medication, performed the physical exam, and assessed for adverse events.  His findings are documented in the patients progress note. Research nurse reinforced that patient should contact treatment team if her status changes or she experiences any adverse effects. column2: Treatment note; Week #13

Patient presented, accompanied by her family, for week #13  of treatment with M7824, required labs and restaging CT Scan were completed.  Dr. Rechache reconciled all home medication, performed the physical exam, and assessed for adverse events.  His findings are documented in the patients progress note.    Dr. Redman met with patient, reviewed labs, reported adverse events, and current status.  Patient notified team (Dr. Strauss) on 08/11/19, that she had developed left side facial weakness, on set 08/10/19, which had gotten progressively worst. Dr. Strauss advised her to go to her nearest urgent care center for evaluation and have the physician call him.  Dr. Strauss spoke with the physician who diagnosed her with Bells Palsy.  She was give a 7 day course of prednisone, 40 mg daily.  During her visit today, she notes her symptoms have not completely resolved.  Dr. Redman decided to hold her week #13 dose of M7824.  The plan is for her to continue with the oral steroids at 30 mg for 1 week, then taper to 20 mg starting on 08/27/19, for one week. All her labs results were within normal limits, with nothing clinically significant.   Research nurse reinforced that patient should contact treatment team if her status changes.  Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for next clinic visit and reassessment of her symptoms.  If resolved, she will have week # 15 dose of M7824.  She did have social work and psychiatry follow up contact during this visit.    All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Redman and Dr. Strauss.
Missed doses...
Week #13 dose held due to Bells Palsy/steroid tx

Due to the increased spread of the skin rash, and continuing facial nerve disorder, Dr. Strauss and Dr. Floudas have decided to hold her week # 27 dose of M7824 for this week.  Research nurse reinforced that patient should contact treatment team if her status changes or her current symptoms get worst.  Patient will continue on oral steroid at 20 mg daily, then start 10 mg daily in a few days when the prior dose is completed. Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks  for Week # 29 clinic visit.  All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Strauss and Dr. Floudas.

column2: Treatment note; Visit:  Week # 9

Patient presents accompanied by her husband for week # 9 of the HPV Trap protocol; her required routine and research labs were collected.  Dr. Mian performed her physical assessment, reconciled her concomitant medications, reviewed all prior adverse events and new complaints.  His findings are documented in the patients progress note.  Dr. Sater met with patient and reviewed her adverse events, symptoms, and symptom management.  Patient admits she is not taking the long acting morphine every twelve hours as prescribed; she only takes it once at night and not the morning dose. She also does not take the short acting narcotic for breakthrough, she only takes Tylenol or an NSAID.  Research nurse reinforced that not taking the morning dose of the long acting narcotis is setting her up for rebound pain, which she admits she experiences at night.  Research nurse suggested patient try taking the prescribed dose of the long acting pain medication twice daily for the next 7 days to see if she gets better pain relief.  Patient agrees she will try. Based todays labs which are within normal limits and her current status, Dr. Sater has approved her treatment of M7824 for week #9. Patient will return in two weeks for clinic and treatment for week #11.  Research nurse reinforced that patient should call her treatment team if her status changes.  Adverse Events Summary to follow in another progress note.

column2: Treatment note; Week # 21

Patient presents accompanied by her husband for week #21 clinic visit, all required labs were drawn.   NP Gloria Jackson, performed her physical assessment, reconciled her concomitant medications, and reviewed her prior and new adverse events complaints.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress note.    Dr. Strass and Dr. Brownell from dermatology, met with them both,  reviewed all the adverse events with patient and discussed her current status.  Patient continues to have pruritus, which is related to the M7824; she has lesions on her torso, legs, and arms.  She continually itches the areas, causing skin breakage and bleeding. Dr. Brownell assessed her skin and reviewed the medications he had prescribed for her.  Patient states she stopped taking the oral Acitretin which was ordered on 04/16/19.  She took it for about 5 days, but stopped after experiencing external ear discomfort, including a burning sensation and then subsequent peeling.  She states the burning sensation resolved immediately after she stopped the Acitretin.  As of todays visit all external ear symptoms have resolved.  Dr. Strauss discussed the next steps in her treatment, including patient possibly going off treatment and starting chemotherapy or another clinical trial.    Due to her current issue with continued pruritis, Dr. Strauss advised patient he will start her on an oral steroid course for 2 weeks.  She will return to clinic in 2 weeks for follow up and an early restaging scan to evaluate her disease.  The M7824 dose will be held at this time.  All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Strauss.

column2: On-study note; Week # 1

Patient accompanied by his wife, presented for Week 1 of treatment with M7824. Patient has been deemed eligible for protocol 18-C-0056, he was consented; and will receive his Week #1 treatment today.  Eligibility checklist reviewed by Dr. Julius Strauss; calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance  is 76 ml/min,  based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine from 6/25/19.  Nurse Practitioner Gloria Jackson performed the physical exam and reconciled home medications, her findings are documented in the patient progress note.   Dr. Strauss discussed the possible side effects of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  He discussed symptom management; including calling treatment team to report side effects immediately at onset.  Research nurse provided patient and his wife with his study calendar of visits and the important phone numbers to contact his treatment team.  Research nurse reviewed patent's medical history/symptoms, and current medications; which are documented in his first registration note from the initial screening visit.  He is on Crestor for hypercholesterolemia, and Pradaxa for his history of atrial fibulation. He takes calcium with vitamin D to help supplement his bone health.  He is on monthly Zometa for metastatic bone disease.    Baseline Review/Findings:  Fatigue from prior treatment and radiation, which is relieve by rest. Dry mouth from prior radiation treatment, has no dietary alterations at this time.
Authored: Protocol Note

column1: Last Updated: 07/09/2019 13:27 by Francis, Deneise C (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,7/9/19,CC-CRIS,

column2: On-study note; Baseline Symptoms/Findings

Skin Disorders - Actinic Keratosis, initially diagnosed in 2005, r/t sun exposure over the years. Fatigue - relieved with rest, onset 01/2018, related to disease, also prior radiation and chemotherapy. Dry Mouth - no dietary alteration, onset 01/2018, related to prior radiation.  07/09/19 Baseline Lab Abnormalities: TSH Increased, grade 1 - prior history of elevation while on Keytruda immunotherapy, related to the therapy, no history of diagnosed hypothyroidism. Anemia, grade 2 - related to prior radiation and chemotherapy. Platelet Count Decreased, grade 1 - related to prior radiation and chemotherapy. Lymphocyte Count Decreased, grade 3 - related to prior radiation and chemotherapy. White Blood Cells Decreased, grade 1 - related to prior radiation and chemotherapy.
Authored: Protocol Note

column1: Last Updated: 07/25/2019 15:25 by Francis, Deneise C (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,7/9/19,CC-CRIS,

column2: Treatment note; Week # 3

Patient accompanied by his wife, presented for week #3 of M7824 treatment, required routine and research labs were collected.  Gloria Jackson, DNP, reconciled all home medications, assessed for adverse events, and performed the patients physical exam.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress note.  Dr. Strauss met with patient, reviewed todays lab results, discussed patients reported symptoms, and current status. The patient states he tolerated Week # 1 infusion well on 07/09/19.  However, when they returned to the hotel, he noted intermittent chest tightness the same night; he denied pain, discomfort, dizziness, or shortness of breath.  He states the tightness did not affect his ADLs and he performed his normal exercise without any difficulties; this tightness resolved after 2 days.  He had onset of rash with itching, as noted in the NPs progress note, around day 3 post treatment, and it is ongoing today.  Dermatology was called, came and consulted with the team and patient in the exam room.  Dr. Brownell suggested topical scalp spray Fluocinonide, topical skin cream Triamcinolone, and Hydroxyzine for his rash and itching; these were all ordered.  Patient describes itching as mild and tolerable, it does not affect his sleep.    Dr. Strauss reviewed labs results, most were within normal limits; those with abnormal findings, if not addressed were not clinically significant.  Baseline labs abnormalities remain stable or have improved.  Dr. Strauss has approved week #3 dose of M7824, the patient will receive his infusion tomorrow morning in the Day Hospital.  Patient will return in 2 weeks for clinic and treatment.  Research nurse reinforced that he should call if his skin symptoms become worst.  All adverse events were discussed with Dr. Strauss.

Dr. Abdul Sater advised patient of the increase in his serum creatinine.  Since patient does not have a history of renal issues, IV hydration was given yesterday after clinic with repeat acute panel .  A nephrology consults was also requested. Patient continues with persistent cough; the Flonase and Prilosec prescribed at last visit was not effect.  Due to the nature of the cough, an ENT consult was scheduled.  Based on patient's status Dr. Abdul Sater did approve the week # 9 dose of M7824, which patient is receiving today.  Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week #11, he will have early restaging scans based on scan results from week # 7. Research nurse reinforced that he should call if his skin symptoms become worst or his status changes.  All adverse events were reviewed and discussed with Dr. Abdul Sater.

His earlly restaging CT scans, which had been planned for week # 11, will be done at his week # 13 time-point.  All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Abdul Sater and Dr. Strauss.

column2: Adverse Events Summary Update

Patient was discharged from local facility on 09/16/19.   Initial Admit: 09/12/19  Admit Diagnosis: Acute COPD exacerbated by Acute Bronchitis and Focal Bronchiectasis (right middle lobe and right lower lobe), resulting in intractable cough and dyspnea. ED assessments included chest X-ray, labs, blood cultures (were negative), and VQ Scan on 09/13/19, negative for PE.  He received IV Rochephine and IV Doxycycline during is work up in the ED prior to admission.  Prior chest CT on 09/09/19, had diagnosed patient with Acute Bronchitis & Bronchiectasis, for which he was being treated with Levaquin and Mucinex after seeing a Pulmonologist on 09/11/19.    During admission he was treated with IV Solu-Medrol, Bronchodilators, and supplemental oxygen therapy.  Pulmonologist re-evaluated patient after treatment and found no indication for a bronchoscopy.  Patient was discharged home on oral steroid (Prednisone (Deltasone) 10 mg tabs) taper starting on 09/17/19, Albuterol HFA inhaler, and Levaquin, as directed.   Follow up with local pulmonologist, 2-3 weeks, and with NIH Clinic on 09/30/19.  He will follow up with local primary care MD in the interim.  Outside medical records uploaded in CRIS EMR.  All adverse events reviewed with Dr. Julius Strauss.

column2: Treatment note; Week #19

Patient presented yesterday, accompanied by his wife, for week #19 clinic and treatment;  restaging scans and required routine labs were completed.  Dr. Jenkins reconciled all home medications, assessed for adverse events, and performed the patients physical exam. Her findings are documented in the patients progress note.  Dr. Abdul Sater met with patient, reviewed lab results, reported adverse events and patients current status.  He discussed the results of the restaging scan, which continue to be stable, with a mixed response.   Patients prior report of reoccurrence of his bronchial/bronchiectasis symptoms have all resolved.  He did receive pre/post IV hydration prophylaxis due to his history of acute renal insufficieny (AKI) and receiving CT contrast dye for his scans today.  His lab results were within normal limits; his anemia continues to be stable, the labs today were drawn post his IV pre-hydration in preparation for his CT scans, thus his hemoglobin may have been dilutional.  The CBC lab was repeated and his hemoglobin was 8.0 mg/dl; he was asymptomatic for anemia thus Dr. Abdul Sater decided not to transfuse him. His serum creatinine continues to be stable.  All other lab abnormalities are stable based on baseline. His bisphosphonate therapy was switched from Zometa to Denosumab (Xgeva) because it is not nephrotoxic compared to the Zometa.  Research nurse provided patient with teaching handout on the Xgeva; reinforcing calcium with vitamin D supplementation.  Dr. Abdul Sater advised patient to increase his oral calcium supplementation to twice daily.    Based on patients current status Dr. Abdul Sater did approved week # 19 dose of M7824 treatment which was given today.  Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week #21 clinic and treatment.  Research nurse advised patient to call if his status changes.   He was also given a copy of his current lab results so his local oncologist will follow up on his anemia status at his schedule lab draw next week.   All adverse events were reviewed and discussed with Dr. Abdul Sater.

Dr. Abdul Sater met with patient, reviewed lab results, reported adverse events and patients current status.  Patient presented complaining of constant and increased right upper abdominal chest wall area pain.  The pain is positional, worst when supine or reclining, slightly improved if sitting up straight.  He can only sleep on his right side to get comfort.  The pain has gotten worst since his last clinic visit.  His heart rate was elevated to the 130s during vital sign assessment.  A stat ECG was ordered, showing arrhthymias, atrial flutter and atrial fibrillation.  The patient does have a prior history of atrial fibrillation, with his last intervention about 2 years ago. The Rapid Response team was called to assess patient due to the arrhthymias; the decision was made to admit him for cardiac consultation and monitoring.     He also reported another episode of cough and dyspnea after flying home on 11/14/19.  He used his inhaler but had to seek treatment on 11/15/19 at his local urgent care.  He was prescribed a Medrol Dose Pack, 4 mg tabs for 6 days.  He was also prescribed Augmentin 875 mg for 7 days.  He reported his symptoms resolved by 11/24/19.    All lab values are within normal limits, any abnormalities are stable based on baseline, and are not clinically significant.   Based on patients current status Dr. Abdul Sater advised patient his Week #21 dose of M7824 treatment would be held and skipped for this treatment period.  Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week #23, early restaging scans at 4 weeks post last scans and clinic.  All adverse events were reviewed and discussed with Dr. Abdul Sater.

Patient did receive radiation for target lesion #1, right T7 Paravertebral mass, thus this lesion is non-evaluable.  Patient reports his prior report of fatigue which affected his ADL's has improved within the last 5 days.  He states he is finally starting to 'feel like myself again'.  His appetite has also improved, he did use ensure to help supplement his nutrition.  He feels these symptoms were due to the radiation treatment he received. His skin toxicities are resolving, pruritus has resolved.  Lab results are within normal limits, with any abnormal results not clinically significant or stable per baseline.  The plan is for patient to return to clinic in 6 weeks for follow up with restaging scans and decisions about the next steps for treatment of his disease.  Dr. Abdul Sater reinforced that patient should contact treatment team if his status changes.   All adverse events were reviewed and discussed with Dr. Abdul Sater.

column2: Off-treatment note; Week  # 35 Follow Up/Restaging

Patient presented, accompanied by his wife, for week #35 restaging and follow up visit; required labs, research, ECG, and restaging scan was completed. He did receive one liter of Normal Saline hydration post CT scan yesterday for his renal insufficiency.   Research nurse discussed the protocol long term follow up policy with patient and his wife; he will be contacted annually by telephone for follow up. column2: On-study note; Week 1

Patient has been deem eligible for protocol 18-C-0056, she was consented; and will receive her Week #1 treatment today.  Eligibility checklist reviewed by Dr. Julius Strauss; calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine is 90 ml/min. Research nurse provided her with her study calendar of visits and the important phone numbers to contact her treatment team.  Reinforced the possible side effects of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  Reinforced symptom management; including calling treatment team to report side effects immediately at onset.  Research nurse reviewed patent's medical history/symptoms, and current medications; which are documented in her first registration note from the initial screening visit.    Medical History/Interventions: Gastrointestinal Reflux, related to past chemotherapy, 01/2017, takes Pantoprazole. Essential hypertension and hypercholesterolemia history, onset more than 15 years, currently not on medication for either. Seasonal allergies, onset more than 5 years, takes Montelukast and Xyzal. Degenerative arthritis pain to bilateral feet, onset more then 5 years ago, takes Diclofenac DR.

column1: Last Updated: 01/24/2019 17:43 by Francis, Deneise C (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,1/23/19,CC-CRIS,

column2: Follow up symptom management

Patient emailed treatment team on Friday, 2/1/19, stating that she was having loose stool, about 12 times a day, which is above her baseline of 4-6 formed stools per day.  She states the increased stools started on 1/23/19, the day after she received the Neupogen injection; however it was not a concern at the time because the stools were formed and sometimes she does have more stools than baseline depending on what she eats.  However on the weekend of 1/26/19, she noticed consistency change to very soft and loose.  She started to have stools whenever she went to the bathroom to urinate; she denies watery diarrhea, but does report intermittent mild abdominal cramping with the loose stools.  Dr. Strauss did contact patient on Friday, 2/1/19; and suggested she report to her local oncologist for labs and stool sample, which she did.    Research nurse emailed patient today, requesting she have her oncologist office fax a copy of the lab results from Friday.  Patient states her symptoms have improved and she will have the oncologist office fax us the labs results.  She said the stool samples have not resulted yet.
Authored: Protocol Note

column1: Last Updated: 02/05/2019 11:08 by Francis, Deneise C (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,1/23/19,CC-CRIS,

column2: Patient emailed her study treatment team on Sunday, 02/10/19, to report that she noticed blood in her urine on Saturday, 02/09/19. She reported that she wears an incontinence pad and the urine was pink tinged. Other than the mild hematuria, patient was asymptomatic. She has a baseline history of urinary urgency, urinary frequency, and urinary incontinence related to 2 prior episodes of pelvic radiation for her disease.  She reports she had a similar episode of blood tinged urine last year, sought treatment and was given Bactrim.  Patient advised the team that she planned to go to a nearby urgent care facility to be evaluated.  Dr. Gatti-Mays communicated with the patient, advised patient that she agreed with her plan and requested that she contact the team with the outcome of her visit.   This morning the patient emailed a copy of the urgent care clinic summary from yesterday; she had a urinalysis, urine culture was sent, which is still pending. She was prescribed Sulfamethoxazole/Trimethoprim (Bactrim), dose 200-40 mg/5 ml liquid, 5 ml orally, twice a day for a 7 day course. In her communication with Dr. Gatti-Mays this morning, she is still asymptomatic, and the color of her urine is clearing up.  She was advised by the urgent care clinic to follow up in 1 week or sooner if symptoms worsen.  The patient has her next scheduled NIH clinic visit next week on 2/19/19.  Results of UA noted below, report will be uploaded in patients EMR.  Pinnacle Health ABC, LLC, 2323 Linglestown Rd., Suite 201B, Harrisburg, PA, 17110 (717) 540-9355  Diagnostic Test Results Lab Acquired: 02/10/19 Test Name Result HIL Reference Range URINALYSIS DIPSTICK -- Profile --   UA GLUCOSE Negative   UA KETONES Negative   UA PH 5.5   UA BLOOD Small    UA COLOR Yellow UA BILIRUBIN Negative  IJA SPECIFIC GRAVITY 1.010  IJA PROTEIN Negative  UA NITRITE Negative UA LEUKOCYTES Trace  IJA CLARITY Clear

Agree with above. When I spoke with Ms X this morning, she denies any visible blood clots in the urine - just pink urine. She reports worsening of her baseline frequency, urgency and incontinence at the onset of symptoms which have now improved. I discussed with her that we have seen some bleeding/oozing from patients on M7824 and specifically that we have seen this in patients who have received prior radiation. She has had prior pelvic RT during her initial treatment for her anal cancer.   She knows that if her symptoms worsen, she develops blood clots, or she has any other concerns she should contact us immediately. She will follow-up with us on Wednesday when her urine cx is resulted.
Authored: Protocol Note
Co-Signer: Protocol Note

column1: Last Updated: 02/11/2019 15:57 by Gatti-Mays, Margaret (MD)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,1/23/19,CC-CRIS,

column2: Patient emailed treatment team on 02/13/19; she states the Urgent Care centered called to report her urine culture was negative for UTI.  She sates she continues to have the mild hematuria, with pink tinged urine; she does not have clots.  She also states she is having more urinary incontinence than her normal baseline, with mild bladder spasms.    Dr. Gatti- Mays advised her to discontinue taking the Bactrim since the UTI work up was negative.  She prescribe the antispasmodic drug, Pyridium.  She counseled patient on the side effects of the Pyridium including urine color change to orange and possible orange tears.  She advised the patient to continue to monitor for clots and to let the  team know if clots occur.  She called the drug into patients local pharmacy.    Patient advised Team that she does not have a local urologist when asked if she wanted to see one locally.  Patient is scheduled for clinic visit next Tuesday, 2/19/19, for week # 5 on the study; Urology consult was ordered and scheduled for 2/20/19 at 1 pm on OP3.  Patient is aware of consult and will schedule her travel accordingly.
Authored: Protocol Note

She states she is still having mild forgetfulness since returning from her vacation 2 weeks ago; she may forget parts of a recipe she has used in the pass or where she placed an item. Dr. Abdul Sater, suggested we add a CT Brain to her restaging scan at her next visit. Patient is agreeable with this. Her anemia is also stable, and she has a slight elevation in her serum calcium, which is not clinically significant, will continue to monitor. column2: Follow Up # 1

Patient presents for her first follow up visit post her EOT on 01/07/20; required routine labs and restaging scan completed.  Dr. Pegna performed the physical assessment, reconciled all concomitant medications, and assessed all prior and new adverse events.  His findings are documented in the patients progress note.      Dr. Strauss and the research nurse spoke with patient via teleconference with Dr. Pegna.  Dr. Strauss reviewed her labs, adverse events, and current status.  He discussed the results of her restaging scan which shows she continues to have a complete response to the M7824.   Patient does report a new Keratoacanthoma lesion above her left eyelid, onset about 2 weeks ago.  She states it is basically asymptomatic except for an occasional itch; she uses the prescribed Tretinoin ointment as needed.  Her prior reports of rash to her waist and memory (fog) impairment have all resolved.  Lab results are within normal limits except for expected white blood cell abnormalities based on her MDS diagnosis.  Dr. Strauss discussed her low ANC of 380 today and  reinforced neutropenic precautions.  He also recommended she contact her Hematologist at JHU to provide them with a copy of her lab result from today.   Patient will continue to be followed by her local oncologist and JHU hematologist for supportive care for her MDS.  Dr. Strauss advised her to call the research team if her KA lesion starts to get worst requiring dermatology interventions.  The patient will return to clinic in 3 months for restaging and follow up visit # 2.   All adverse events were reviewed and discussed with Dr. Strauss.

column1: Last Updated: 05/17/2019 13:12 by Lamping, Elizabeth A (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,9/25/18,CC-CRIS,

column2: On-study note; 18-C-0056 Week # 1

Patient accompanied by her husband presented for week #1 of treatment with M7824 investigational drug product. Patient has been deemed eligible for protocol 18C0056, she signed the inform consent document; and will receive her  first treatment today.  Protocol eligibility checklist reviewed and verified by Dr. Julius Strauss.  The calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance is 88 ml/min, based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine from 08/27/19 baseline screening labs.   Dr. Clara performed the physical exam, reviewed medical history including current symptoms, and reconciled home medications, his findings are documented in the patient progress note.   Dr. Strauss discussed the possible side effects and possible toxicities of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  He discussed and explained symptom management; including calling the treatment team or after hours covering provider to report side effects immediately at onset.  Research nurse provided patient with the study calendar of visits and the important phone numbers to contact the research treatment team and after-hours solid tumor covering provider and page operator.  The patient and family member were given the opportunity to ask questions, which were all addressed to their satisfaction.  Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week #3 clinic and treatment.  Baseline Symptoms/Finding: Rectal Pain - mild, intermittent left buttocks anorectal pressure and cramping. Hearing Impaired - bilateral hearing lost, attributes to loud music, uses hearing aids. Patient states her hearing was tested in 2010, loss is in the high registers.  She can hear without the hearing aids, but it sounds muffled.
Authored: Protocol Note

column1: Last Updated: 09/12/2019 08:32 by Francis, Deneise C (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,9/10/19,CC-CRIS,

column2: Treatment note; Week # 3

Patient presents accompanied by her husband for Week #3 of treatment on the clinical trial; all required routine and research labs were collected.  Dr. Samour reconciled her home medications, reviewed lab results, assessed for adverse events, and performed the physical exam.  His findings are documented  in the patient progress note.  Dr. Strauss met with patient, reviewed labs and discussed her current status.  Patient has no complaints at this time, she states she tolerated her week # 1 infusion well.  She had emailed Dr. Strauss last week to advise him of a definitive diagnosis of intermittent pruritus to her upper back which she had been experiencing for the past 2 years.  She saw her Dermatologist on 09/17/19, and was given a diagnosis with Notalgia Paresthetica, which is a peripheral sensory disorder characterized by intermittent itching to the same area of the upper and middle back.  Her Dermatologist had recommended Capsaicin cream.  After one application of the cream, she had to wipe it off due to a burning sensation.  She currently has no intervention at this time.  Her lab results are within normal limits; based on this and her current status, Dr. Strauss has approved Week # 3 of M7824 infusion.  The patient will return in 2 weeks for clinic and treatment.  Research nurse reinforced for he to call her treatment team if her status changes.  No adverse events to report at this time.
Authored: Protocol Note

column1: Last Updated: 10/25/2019 21:13 by Lamping, Elizabeth A (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,9/10/19,CC-CRIS,

column2: Treatment note; Week # 9

Patient presents accompanied by her husband for Week #9 of treatment on the clinical trial; all required labs were collected.  Dr. Jenkins reconciled her home medications, reviewed lab results, assessed for adverse events, and performed the physical exam.  Her findings are documented  in the patient progress note.  Dr. Strauss met with patient, reviewed lab results, assessed for adverse events, and discussed her current status.  She has new complaints of a maculo-papular rash to bilateral hands and forearms. She has also noticed mild, bleeding at intestinal stoma site when she cleans the site and changes her appliance; there were no visible clots and bleeding resolves with application of new appliance.  The patient did have a PET/CT scan yesterday prior to her Radiation Oncology consult; this scan was to aid in the decision whether give palliative radiation for rectal pain.  The decision was made not to radiate at this time.  Her lab results are within normal limits, her increased alkaline phosphatase and ALT will be monitored.  Any other lab abnormalities which were not addressed are not clinically significant.  The patient was advised to discontinue use of Ibuprofen for pain, she was given a prescription of Oxycodone, which she has used in the past and it was effective for her pain. Based on her current status Dr. Strauss has approved week # 9 of M7824 infusion.  The patient will return in 2 weeks for clinic and early restating scan (4 weeks) to re-evaluate/confirm prior disease progression seen on the week # 7 restaging scan.  She will also have a liver Ultra Sound and liver biopsy at the next visit; the prep for these two procedures were discussed, including stopping all NSAIDs 7 days prior to the biopsy.  Research nurse reinforced  to call her treatment team if her status changes.  All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Strauss.

column2: Treatment note; Week # 19

Patient presents for week 19 M7824 treatment on protocol; required labs and restaging CT scans were completed.  Dr. Jenkins reconciled all home medications, reviewed labs results, assessed for adverse events, and performed the his physical examination.  Her findings are documented in the patient process note.  Dr. Floudas met with patient, reviewed labs, adverse events, and current status.  He discussed the findings of the CT scan which showed an increase in a pericardial effusion which had been identified on the baseline CT scan.  Patient also reports cold symptoms (Upper Respiratory Infection), and a nasal wash ordered and performed. Lab result are within normal limits; anomalities are stable per baseline or are not clinically significant.  Based on patient's status today, Dr. Floudas advised him that his week 19 M7824 treatment will be held.  Dr. Floudas discussed how the team plans to monitor the Pericardial effusion; an EKG was done today.  A Echocardiogram is scheduled for 2 weeks when patient returns for next clinic visit.  Patient verified that he was aware of having the effusion because his local MD had referred him for an Echo after the pericardial effusion was seen on a prior scan.  He states he can contact the cardiologist that performed the echo if he becomes symptomatic at home.   He knows to contact the research team if his status changes.   All adverse events reviewed and discussed with Dr. Floudas.

column2: On-study note; Week # 1

Patient accompanied by her mother-in-law, presented for Week 1 of treatment with M7824. Patient has been deemed eligible for protocol 18-C-0056, she was consented; and will receive her Week #1 treatment tomorrow.  Eligibility checklist reviewed by Dr. Gatti-Mays; calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance  is 182 ml/min,  based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine from 7/9/19.  Dr. Carter performed the physical exam,   reconciled home medications, reviewed baseline medical history and current symptoms.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress note.   Dr. Gatti-Mays discussed the possible side effects of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  She discussed symptom management; including calling treatment team to report side effects immediately at onset.  The patient as given the opportunity to ask questions, which were answered to her satisfaction.  Research nurse provided patient with her study calendar of visits and the important phone numbers to contact the treatment team.  The patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week # 3 clinic and treatment.  Baseline Symptoms/Findings:  08/2018 Nausea, intermittent, daily, on Compazine, related to prior therapy an possible disease. 10/2018 Laryngeal Nerve Palsy, which caused vocal cords paralysis, was treated by injection with some relief.  Related to mediastinal mass/disease. 04/2019 Dyspnea on exertion, related to disease. 03/2015 Tinnitus, related to prior Cisplatin chemotherapy. 07/16/19 Peripheral Sensory Neuropathy, minor numbness & tingling to toes/feet. Related to prior chemotherapy. 07/16/19 Lymphocyte Count Decreased, related to prior chemotherapy and radiation. 05/2019 Non-cardiac Chest Pain, left side,  related to disease. 07/2019 Back Pain, lower back, possible related to disease or possible generative changes in bone. 04/2019 Constipation, occasional, intermittent, related to medications.
Authored: Protocol Note

column2: Treatment note; Week # 3

Patient accompanied by her husband presents for week # 3 of M7824 treatment on study; required routine and research labs were completed. The patient requested an early visit due to vacation later this week.  Gloria Jackson, DNP, reconciled all home medications, reviewed all prior and new adverse events, and performed the physical assessment.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress note.  Dr. Gatti-Mays met with patient, reviewed today's lab results, reviewed reported adverse events, and patient's current status.  As noted in the providers note, the patient's recent symptoms of nausea, vomiting, anorexia, and constipation have improved; overall hydration status improved now that nausea is controlled.  Patient will receive one liter of normal saline to help with IV hydration due to her recovering from these symptoms. An MRI of the lumbar sacral spine was ordered and will be scheduled.  Patient's lab results are within normal limits; lab abnormalities that have not been addressed are not clinically significant.  Dr. Gatti-Mays has approved week # 3 dose of M7824, the patient will return in 2 weeks for week 5 clinic and treatment.  All adverse events reviewed with Dr. Gatti-Mays.

Patient accompanied by her husband presents for week #5 study visit; required routine labs were completed.  Gloria Jackson, DNP, reconciled all home medications, reviewed all prior and new adverse events, and performed the physical assessment.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress note.  The patient was recently discharged, on 08/06/19, from the hospital after having surgery for partial cord compression, with laminectomy and tumor resection to L2-L4, affecting her right lower extremity.  She is scheduled to receive radiation for two weeks, starting today, for a sacral mass, that is affecting her left lower extremity, as described in the neurosurgery progress notes prior to her discharge. She is also constipated, with last bowel movement 9 days ago; she will restart lactulose, which she had stopped taking.  Patient will be here daily for radiation, advised to contact team if she feels she needs supportive care.  All adverse events reviewed with Dr. Abdul Sater

column2: Treatment note; Week #7 Visit on 08/27/19

Patient yesterday, 08/27/19,  accompanied by her husband and Mother for week #7 study visit; required restaging scans, routine and research labs were completed.  Dr. Carter, reconciled all home medications, reviewed all prior and new adverse events, and performed the physical assessment.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress note.  The patient's M7824 treatment has been on hold due to recent spinal surgery and radiation therapy.  Her last M7824 treatment date was 07/29/19.  Patient was on a steroids related to her recent surgical procedure; her dose was tapered and she took her last dose of steroids on 08/26/19, as directed by Radiation Oncologist.   Dr. Abdul Sater met with patient, reviewed today's lab results, reviewed reported adverse events, and patient's current status.  She continued to have severe fatigue, decreased appetite, and tachycardia, as noted in Dr. Carter's assessment.  Dr. Abdul Sater discussed these continued issues with patient and the decision was made to admit the patient to the inpatient unit for further clinical work up and evaluation.    Dr. Strauss and Dr. Abdul Sater reviewed the results of her restaging scan, which showed disease progression compared to baseline scan.  She also has tumor affecting her arteries and near her heart, which is causing her continued tachycardia.  Other than severe fatigue she has no cardiac symptoms at this time.  They met with the patient and her family and explained the scan results.  They had the discussion about what the next steps for treatment would be based on patient's wishes.  They also advised that Dr. Thomas wanted to discuss another clinical trial with the patient and her family.  The patient and her husband advised they will think about their options and discuss this with the team at a later date.  Plan is for cardiology consults, cortisol stimulation test, nutrition consult, and pain/palliative care consult.  The week 7 dose of M7824 will not be given.  All adverse events reviewed with Dr. Abdul Sater

column2: wk 15 remote patient update

On 3/21/20, patient contacted study team via email to report that she had UTI symptoms (bladder pressure, burning with urination, slight blood noted in urine) and that she was starting on antibiotic Macrobid for 7 day course.  On 3/24/20, patient reported she was Beginning to feel much better now that Macrobid is doing its job. No further blood in urine and has not yet had a sore throat/esphagus, a possible side effect of recent Rad Onc treatment.  Patient reports she is In 2 week mandatory isolation since we came back, required by Canada upon her return home.   Patient will not come to NIH for week 15 protocol time point due to travel restriction advisements in place at this time. Treatment hold of study drug will be continued per PI. Patient will not return to NIH until 5/5/20, at which time she will have re-staging scheduled for protocol and for radiation oncology follow up.

column2: Treatment note; Week # 7

Patient presented accompanied by his wife for week # 7 clinic visit, required labs were collected.  His week #7 restaging scans were delayed to be performed in 2 weeks at week 9, due to recent scans he had done at home.  His M7824 treatment was held at week # 5 due to complaint of dyspnea with for which oral steroid was started.  Dr. Carter reconciled his home medications, assessed for adverse events and performed his physical exam.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress note.  Dr. Floudas met with patient, reviewed his lab results, adverse events, and current status.  The patient continues to have dyspnea, which is not improving; he had stopped his steroids in error about a week ago.  The lab results where within normal limits; abnormalities which were not addressed are not clinically significant. He was started on Synthroid for his increased TSH. His rising liver enzymes which are  slightly above baseline will be monitored.    Based on his current status, Dr. Floudas advised patient that the M7824 study drug would be held for week # 7 due to his worsening dyspnea.  A pulmonary consult was requested and completed.  Restaging scans were added on for this visit after patient was assessed today, however both CT scanners were down.  The steroid, Prednisone was ordered restart for today with instructions not to stop until a phone call assessment by one of research team attending physicians.  The plan is for patient to return in 2 weeks for restaging scans, Echocardiogram, pulmonary function test and clinic.  Dr. Floudas reinforced that patient should contact his local oncologist or go to ED if his symptoms gets worst.  All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Floudas.
Missed doses..., Weeks # 5 & 7
Held due to Dyspnea

column2: Treatment note; Week # 49

Patient presented for week 49 follow up yesterday, her M7824 has been on hold due to Keratoacanthomas; required labs were collected and restaging CT scan was completed.  Dr. Abdul Sater performed her physical exam, reconciled her concomitant medications; reviewed all prior and current adverse events.  His findings are documented in the patient's progress notes.  He reviewed her restaging scan results, as documented in his progress note; the next steps as far as her treatment was discussed. He completed teaching on Acitretin, which will be prescribed to patient when she restates the HPV Trap study drug, to help prevent Keratoacanthomas.  Patient will return tomorrow for full body photography, as required by Dr. Brownell of Dermatology, with each restaging time point.  She will also have fasting lipid panel collected in preparation for starting the Acitretin.  If the final plan is for her to restart the HPV Trap, she will return to clinic in 2 weeks to restart the drug.   All adverse events reviewed and discussed with Dr. Abdul Sater

column2: On-study note; Week # 1

Patient accompanied by family members, presented to screen and start treatment with M7824 investigational drug product, on protocol 18-C-0056. Protocol eligibility checklist  was reviewed and verified by Dr. Julius Strauss. Patient has been deemed eligible for enrollment on the clinical trial.  She signed the inform consent document yesterday; and will receive the first infusion of M7824 today.   The calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance is 101 ml/min, based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine from 11/25/19 labs.   Dr. Pastor performed the physical exam, reviewed medical history including current symptoms, and reconciled home medications including herbal supplements.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress note.     Dr. Strauss discussed the possible side effects and possible toxicities of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  He discussed and explained symptom management; including calling the treatment team or after hours covering provider to report side effects immediately at onset.  He also reviewed her list of herbal supplements and advised her which ones she should discontinue while enrolled on the clinical trial.    Research nurse provided patient with the study calendar of visits and the important phone numbers to contact the research treatment team and after-hours solid tumor covering provider and page operator.  The patient and family member were given the opportunity to ask questions, which were all addressed to their satisfaction.   Baseline findings/symptoms: Fatigue - grade 1, mild currently, does not affect her ADL's and relieved with rest, this is related to disease and prior treatment, onset 06/2019 Anorexia - grade 2, reports no appetite but does force herself to eat, takes 4 supplemental shakes per to help with nutrition, as recommended in prior nutrition consult.  This is related to disease and prior treatment, onset 09/2019.  Pain - grade 2, Upper quadrant/abdominal, radiates to mid back, also pain to left clavicle, currently on pain regimen. This is related to her disease, onset 03/2019. Constipation - grade 1, intermittent,  due to narcotic use for pain usual pattern is 1 bowel movement every 2 days, she is on Senakot bowel regimen daily, does not affect ADLs. This is not related to her disease, is related to pain medication, onset 09/2019. Onset of the above is with her most recent metastatic disease diagnosis,  chemotherapy and radiation, within the last 5 months.  LMP was May 2018, based on FSH, estradiol and LH she is not technically post menopausal.  Dr. Strauss reinforced the use of barrier method of contraception while enrolled on the clinical trial.

column2: Treatment note; Week #3

Patient accompanied by her husband presented for week 3 of treatment on M7824; required research and routine labs were collected.  Dr. McAdams reconciled home medications, assessed for adverse events, and performed the patients physical exam.  Her findings are documented in the patients progress note.   Dr. Floudas met with patient, reviewed labs, adverse events and patients current status.  She is complaining of constipation and not having a normal bowel movement in the last 5 days.  Dr. Floudas reviewed her baseline CT scan from 11/25/19, showing the patient the abdominal film which showed she did have a large amount of stool in her intestine.  He attributes her constipation to the increased use of narcotic pain medications.  He has ordered lactulose for immediate use to relieve her constipation.  She will also get Miralax to use as needed with her stool softeners.  The patient states she did tolerate her week #1 dose of the M7824 without any difficulty.  Her earlier report of nail infection is completely resolved after several applications of topical neosporin antibiotics.  Lab results are within norma limits; abnormal results are not clinically significant if not addressed or are stable based on baseline values.  Dr. Floudas has approved her week # 3 dose of M7824.  The patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week #5 visit.  Research nurse reinforced for her to call team if her status changes.  Adverse events reviewed with Dr. Floudas.

column2: Treatment note; Week # 5

Patient accompanied by her husband and sister presents for week 5 of treatment on M7824; required routine labs were collected.  Dr. Cole reconciled home medications, assessed for adverse events, and performed the patients physical exam.  His findings are documented in the patients progress note.   Dr. Floudas met with patient, reviewed labs, adverse events and patients current status.  She continues to have constipation, with relief only with laxative use.  She has abdominal discomfort with cramping and bloating related to the constipation and ongoing laxative use.  She has new complaints over the week, since 12/18/19, of rectal bleeding when she has stools.  In reviewing her labs, Dr. Floudas advised her hemoglobin level as dropped to 7.6 g/dl compared to her baseline of 9.0 g/dl.  Her bilirubin total has also increased from baseline, which was normal.  Based on her current status of anemia, rectal bleeding with stools,  and increased bilirubin, Dr. Floudas advised patient he will hold her week #5 M7824 dose of today.  The plan will be for her to get a blood transfusion today and restaging CT scans today for increased bilirubin; restaging will be at 4 weeks post start of study.  Dr. Floudas also advised he will request a GI consult due to her symptoms. He will inform patient of additional interventions based on scans and GI consult.  All other lab results are within normal limits or are stable per baseline.  Patient will have 2 week follow up clinic visit for week # 7, no scans.  Dr. Floudas reinforced that patient should inform research team of any changes in her status.  Adverse events reviewed with Dr. Floudas.

column2: Treatment note; Safety Visit - Week #6

Patient presents unaccompanied for safety follow up visit after her discharge for ERCP and common bile duct stenting procedure on 12/26/19, at University of Maryland Medical Center; routine labs were collected.  Dr. Pang reconciled home medications, assessed for adverse events, and performed the patient's physical exam.  Her findings are documented in the patient's progress note.   Dr. Floudas met with patient, reviewed labs, adverse events and patient's current status.  His findings are also included in the patient progress note.  Her lab results, especially her hepatic panel has improved with the stenting procedure.  Patient advised team that supportive network at home has decreased with her sister and mother returning to their homes, so she does not have any family member other than her husband.  She expressed that she is having difficulty finding someone to drive her to her NIH appointments.  Her husband is working and the last few times she attempted to drive a long distance, due to her current status, she fell asleep at the wheel.  She has contacted the ACS but their program does not guarantee she would have a ride to her treatment visits.  Research nurse advised patient we would work with her to help with transportation until she becomes capable to transport herself.  Patient was referred to Pain & Palliative services for supportive assessment and care.   Dr. Floudas reinforced that patient should inform research team of any changes in her status.  She will return to clinic in one week for week #7 clinic and treatment.  Her restaging scan will be on 1/21/20, 4 weeks from her early restaging at week # 5, on 12/24/19.  Adverse events reviewed with Dr. Floudas.

Dr. Sheth reconciled her concomitant medications; reviewed  all prior and current adverse event complaints; and performed her physical exam.  His findings are documented in his progress note.  Dr. Strauss met with patient; reviewed her lab results for today, discussed her adverse events and current status.  He discussed the restaging CT scan results and advised patient of the findings. Research nurse met with patient in the Day Hospital, asked patient if she had any recurrence of the prior report of nausea and vomiting she had prior to the 3/12/19 clinic visit.  She denies any nausea at this time, however she states when she takes her narcotic pain medication, she gets mild nausea afterwards.  She take the prescribed oral antiemetic with relief.  She has not had any emesis episodes since the last reported episodes.   The patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for her week # 9 visit.   Research nurse advised patient she will be contacted with the results of the urine culture, which was collected. Patient presents accompanied by her mother and father for week 9 clinic visit  yesterday, 04/09/19; required labs were collected on 04/08/19.  Dr. Khan reconciled her concomitant medications; reviewed  all prior and current adverse event complaints; and performed her physical exam.  Her findings are documented in her progress note.  Dr. Strauss and Dr. Abdul Sater met with patient and her family; reviewed her lab results for today, discussed her adverse events and current status.  They advised her that with her continued oral mucositis, which was probably related to M7824, they will continue to hold her  treatment for week #9. They did request and got a consult with the Developmental Therapeutics team during this visit to discuss what potential clinical trials patient may be eligible for in the event that there is confirmed disease progression on her next restaging scan in a few weeks.  Because patient has now permanently relocated to Maryland to be near her parents, they suggested she find a local oncologist to establish care outside of NIH.  Patient and her parents agreed with this suggestion.    Based on her results, specifically her continued anemia, she was scheduled and received a blood transfusion today. The patient did have an Ultra Sound of her right leg yesterday  due to increased swelling; this was positive for a DVT.  Her dose of Lovenox was adjusted up with this new finding. Planned urology consult was completed today.  Patient will return to clinic in one week for a follow up visit to monitor her anemia. Patient and family knows to contact treatment team if her status changes.  All adverse events were reviewed and discussed with Dr. Strauss

column2: On-study note; Week # 1

Patient accompanied by her husband, presented for week 1 of treatment with M7824 investigational drug product. Patient has been deemed eligible for protocol 18C0056, she signed the inform consent document; and will receive the first treatment of M7824 today.  Eligibility checklist reviewed and verified by Dr. Abdul Sater.  The calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance is 68 ml/min, based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine from 7/23/19 screening lab results.   Dr. Gandhy performed the physical exam, reviewed medical history including current symptoms, and reconciled home medications, her findings are documented in the patient progress note.   Dr. Abdul Sater discussed the possible side effects and possible toxicities of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  He discussed and explained symptom management; including calling the treatment team or after hours covering provider to report side effects immediately at onset.  Research nurse provided patient with the study calendar of visits and the important phone numbers to contact the research treatment team and after-hours solid tumor covering provider and page operator.  The patient and family member were given the opportunity to ask questions, which were all addressed to their satisfaction.  Baseline Symptoms/Findings: Anorexia, decreased appetite, with onset after she completed her chemotherapy and radiation approximated around July 2018, eating habits are not altered. Fatigue, mild, does not affect ADL's.
Authored: Protocol Note

column2: Telephone follow up call

Research nurse called patient to discuss patient's email regarding her follow up with her local Interventional Radiology on Thursday, 8/22/19.  She had an appointment to evaluate both her biliary/hepatic drains.  She states the radiologist capped the left drain and left the right on connected to the bag to drain.  Later in the evening on Thursday the left drain started to leave at the insertion site and she developed fever and chills, similar to the last time she was capped.  She went to the ED, arrived at 6 pm on Thursday, blood work was done; which all came back within normal lists except for elevated liver panel results.  She was discharged home from the ED on Friday at 2 pm, on a 7 day course of Cefuroxime axetil 500 mg, which she started on Saturday, 08/24/19.  She is currently at work, and both drains are attached to drainage bags, she has not had any fever, chills, or leakage of the left drain since discharge.  Patient will return to NIH for next visit on 09/03/19.  She is scheduled to have hepatic panel done tomorrow with results faxed to research nurse.
Authored: Protocol Note

column2: Treatment note; Week # 9

Patient presents accompanied by a friend for week # 9 clinic visit, required labs were completed.    Dr. Wooley reconciled her current home medications, reviewed reported adverse events, and performed her physical exam.  His findings are documented in the patient progress note.  The M7824 study drug has been on hold since week # 3 (08/20/19), due to increasing liver enzymes.  There was also a recent episode of biliary drain reflux due to malfunction of drainage from upsized drain right biliary drain; this caused additional lab abnormalities of increasing amylase and lipase, dehydration and altered nutrition.  This caused week #7 dose of the study drug to be held.  Dr. Abdul Sater met with patient, reviewed her labs, discussed her reported adverse events, and current status.  Patients right billary drain is now functioning properly; she is able to eat and drink, no reflux of food/fluids into drain.  She received and completed palliative radiation, from 9/25/19 to 10/1/19, of the hepatic/biliary obstruction.  Dr. Abdul Sater advised her that her liver enzyme elevation have improved, and prior pancreatic enzyme elevation are also improved. column2: Treatment note; Week #25, re-staging

Patient presents accompanied by a friend for week # 25 clinic visit, required labs were completed.   Dr. Scorupan reconciled her current home medications, assessed for adverse events, and performed her physical exam.  His findings are documented in the patient progress note.    Dr. Abdul-Sater met with patient, reviewed her labs, adverse events, preliminary reading of CT scan and the current status.  Patient reported right side abdominal pain, tender on palpation, with fever at 100.9 and nausea, onset Saturday, 18 Jan 2020.  Drainage bags added and capped with prophylaxis Cipro initiated and  presenting symptoms resolved, abdominal pain remained persistent. Left bag noted to be draining well with right bag decreased output. Per primary oncologist instruction, right drain flushed with saline and output improved. Monday,  20 Jan 2020, food particles noted in bag, stopcock closed while eating, and drainage decreased. Left middle finger bump noted, onset 18 Jan 2020. Lip lesion is improved s/p shave excision, bilateral shoulder KA sites improved s/p cryotherapy. Dr. Brownell from dermatology called for follow-up consult as documented in his progress note.  Lab results today are within normal limits, labs abnormalities that are not addressed are not clinically significant or stable per baseline. Preliminary CT scan read noted cholecystitis and spontaneous pneumothorax (prior history of pulmonary blebs/artifacts.) and stable disease.  Dr. Abdul-Sater discussed findings with patient and will admit patient for IR consult for cholecystitis and pneumothorax, and will implement interventions based off consult findings. Based on patient's current status, Dr. Abdul-Sater will hold M7824 treatment for today.    All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Abdul-Sater.

column1: Last Updated: 02/27/2019 16:38 by Lamping, Elizabeth A (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,12/11/18,CC-CRIS,

column2: Treatment note; Week 11

Patient presented for week 11 clinic and treatment visit, required lab work was collected and Dr. Samour performed his physical exam.  Dr. Samour reconciled all concomitant medications and reviewed all prior and new adverse events,  his findings are documented in the patient progress note.  The patient has a history of hypothyroidism for which he is on oral medication.  His TSH is elevated today, and his synthroid dose was increased due to this elevation.  Patient advised he should follow up with this local endocrinologist regarding his thyroid studies result.  Patient was also advised to consult with a local cardiologist for his baseline finding of sinus tachycardia.    Dr. Abdul Sater discussed the patient's lab results and adverse events with patient.  He advised him that his week 11 treatment will be held due to increasing liver enzymes, his ALT and AST; the patient had an elevated ALT, grade 1, at baseline prior to starting the M7824.  He advised patient that he wants the patient to have the specific liver enzymes repeated in one week with the patient's primary physician, and have the results faxed to his treatment team here at NIH. Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week 13 clinic and treatment visit.

column2: Treatment note; Week # 13 Clinic and restaging visit

Patient presented for week #13 clinic and treatment visit, required lab work was collected and he completed his restaging CT scan this morning.  Dr. Chau performed his phyiscal exam;  reconciling the patient's concomitant medications; also reviewing all prior and new adverse events.  Dr. Chau's findings are documented in his progress note.  The patient's M7824 investigation drug product was held at his last clinic visit 2 weeks ago, 02/19/19,  due to increasing liver enzymes, ALT and AST.  Dr. Gatti-Mays reviewed the initial results of the patients CT scan, advised him his disease is stable.  She advised the patient of his continued elevated and increasing liver enzymes.  She discussed the possible causes of this elevation, including questioning patient on any medications or herbal supplements he may be taking at home; she advised him to stop the ones he identified.  The plan for this visit is to continue to hold the M7824 and to start the patient on Prednisone, 40 mg daily.  He will need to have liver enzymes labs repeated in one week at home, based on those results, the Prednisone will be tapered if applicable.  She discussed the dosing and administration requirements for the prednisone, reinforcing that he let his primary care MD and endocrinologist know he is starting the steroid.   Patient agreed with the plan.     Research nurse will contact his primary care MD's office to coordinate his repeat lab work.  Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week 15 clinic visit.

column2: Treatment note; Day #15

Patient accompanied by husband, presented to clinic for Day #15 of treatment on NSH-IL12; required research and routine lab s collected. Dr. Burkitt reconciled home medication (new pain medication regimen initiated per pain palliative group locally), adverse events assessed, and physical exam performed. Finding are documented in progress note.   Dr. Gatti-Mays met with patient, reviewed labs, adverse events, and patients current status. Any abnormal results not captured, are deemed not clincally significant. Patient stated that overall her first injection went well. Pt reported fevers that started one day after treatment, with T. Max at 102.5 on day 3, 02/21/2020. Worsening cough noted, that is improved with albuterol nebulizer treatments. On exam, end expiratory wheeze noted in left lung apex. Chest x-ray performed and Dr.Gatti-Mays reviewed with radiologist, and unclear if  opacity noted in lungs is due to radiation vs. tumor growth. Early re-staging visit and pulmonary consult scheduled for next Friday, 03/13/2020. Urine culture results on 02/17/20 yielded Aerococcus sanguinicola, local PCP elected to initiate Ciprofloxacin treatment, with urinalysis results today negative for bacteria. Additionally, patient denies dysuria, hematuria, and frequency. Dr. Gatti-Mays discussed findings with the team, and deemed that patient will proceed with Day #15 treatment today. Patient will return to clinic on 03/13/20 for pulmonology consult and CT scan. Research nurse reinforced importance of contacting study team if her status changes, with special focus on any changes in respiratory status. Patient stated understanding and confirmed that she has pertinent contact information.

column2: On-study note; On Study Note Week #1

Patient presented to clinic to complete screening and start treatment with M7824 investigational drug product on 18C0056. Protocol eligibility checklist reviewed and verified by Dr. Gatti-Mays and Dr. Strauss remotely and by Dr. Abdul-Sater on-site, and pt was deemed eligible to enroll on the clinical trial. Pt signed informed consent today with Dr. Abdul-Sater and witnessed by research nurse via video conference..   Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance is 163 ml/min, based on height and weight and serum creatinine results from 03/19/20. Dr. Peter DeMaria performed physical exam, reviewed medical history, to include current symptoms, and reconciled home medications. Please see progress note for his documented findings.   Dr. Gatti-Mays and Dr. Abdul-Sater discussed the possible side effects of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent. Additionally, stressed the risk of mucosal bleeding and the associated symptoms, and the risk of pneumonitis secondary to radiation therapy and extensive disease in the lung area. They explained symptom management, to include when and how to call the treatment team and after hours coverage. They discussed the importance of reporting side effects promptly to the study team. Patient has important phone numbers and contact information for the study team. The patient stated understanding of all information presented and all questions were answered.    Baseline Findings /Symptoms:  Onset:03/2003, Hypertension, Gr.2, not related to dx, On medication  Onset: 07/2003, Allergic rhinitis, Gr.1, not related to dx  Onset: 12/2011, Bronchospasm (asthma), Gr.2, not related to dx, on medication  Onset:4/2016, Anxiety, Gr.2, related to dx, on medication                 Onset:4/2016, Depression, Gr. 2, related to dx, on medication   Onset:6/2019, Tumor Pain, Gr. 2, related to dx, on medication   Onset: 3/2019, Hemoptysis, Gr. 1, related to dx  Onset:04/2019,Dyspnea, Gr.1, related to dx                 Onset: 04/2019, Cough, Gr. 2, related to dx, on medication                Onset:04/2019, Nausea, Gr. 2, related to dx, on medication                Onset:08/2019,GERD, Gr. 2, related to dx, on medication                 Onset:10/2019,Pericardial Effusion, Gr. 2, related to dx     Onset: 2/2020,Renal & urinary disorders(bacteriuria), Gr.1, related to dx  Onset: 02/2020, Anemia, Gr. 2, related to dx                     Onset:02/2020,Lymph count decrease, Gr.2, related to dx    Onset: 02/2020, Sinus Tachycardia, Gr. 1, not related to dx Onset: 03/03/20, Anorexia, Gr.1, related to diagnosis Onset: 03/17/20, Constipation, Gr. 1, related to medication (morphine)   Patients last dose of chemotherapy was 01/2020, last dose of NSH-IL12 03/03/20, and last fraction of palliative radiation on 03/20/20, many of these findings are attributable to metastatic cancer diagnosis, cancer, and treatment course.  Patient s/p hysterectomy 2016.

Patient presents for restaging and clinic visit for the study; required labs and scans were completed. column1: Last Updated: 05/30/2019 16:04 by Lamping, Elizabeth A (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,12/4/18,CC-CRIS,

column2: On-study note; Treatment note; Week # 1

Patient accompanied by his sister, presented for Week # 1 of treatment with M7824 investigational drug product. Patient has been deemed eligible for protocol 18-C-0056, he signed the inform consent document; and will receive his first treatment with M7824 today.  Protocol eligibility checklist reviewed and verified by Dr. Julius Strauss.  The calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance is 81ml/min, based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine from 11/12/19 screening labs.   Dr. Desai performed the physical exam, reviewed medical history including current symptoms, and reconciled home medications, his findings are documented in the patient progress note.   Dr. Strauss discussed the possible side effects and possible toxicities of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  He reinforced use of barrier method for contraception while on the clinical trial.  He discussed and explained symptom management; including calling the treatment team or after hours covering provider to report side effects immediately at onset. The patient does have a Titanium Portacath, thus the M7824 will be infused via his Portacath.  Research nurse provided patient with the study calendar of visits and the important phone numbers to contact the research treatment team and after-hours solid tumor covering provider and page operator.  The patient and family member were given the opportunity to ask questions, which were all addressed to their satisfaction.  The patient will return in 2 weeks for week # 3 clinic and treatment visit.  Baseline Findings/Symptoms: Gastrointestinal Reflux Disease (GERD), grade 2, since 2018 after his radiation treatment, thus related to radiation and not disease; sometimes causes intermittent nausea.  He was on Omeprazole in the past, but was not at this visit.  Prescription entered for Omeprazole as part of GERD regimen.  Patient refused antiemetic, states any nausea is due to his GERD, and is rare.   Serum creatinine, grade 1, increased due to prior history of renal insufficiency related to Cisplatin chemotherapy in 2018, not related to disease.  Hypothyroidism grade 2, related to prior radiation therapy and probably not disease; currently on Synthroid, TSH is elevated at baseline, will monitor. Tinnitus, intermittent, grade 1, onset in 2018 after receiving chemotherapy, thus not related to disease.

column2: Treatment note; Week #19 re-staging

Patient here today for week #19 clinic visit, required routine labs were collected. Dr. DeMaria reconciled his home medications and supplements, assessed for adverse events, and performed the patient's physical exam.  His findings are documented in the patient progress note.  Dr. Floudas and research nurse talked with patient via video conference. Dr. Floudas reviewed the lab results adverse events, and current status.  Lab results not captured are deemed clinically insignificant.  Patient continues to report improved epistaxis, with decreased frequency. He continues to follow recommendations provided by ENT. Fatigue is still persistent, with this week being a continued improvement. Decreased libido is is unchanged at this time. Patient will continue to assess for any changes in its status. TSH elevation noted at this visit, Levothyroxine dose increased to 150mcg, with patient verbalizing understanding of this change. Patient reported mild headache and rhinorrhea for two days, that has since resolved.   Imaging on 03/19/20 showed some increase in tumor size. Per Dr. Floudas, awaiting official read by Bagheri and RECIST assessment. In the absence of clinical symptoms, will treat today, with repeat imaging in 4-weeks instead of 6. Dr. Demaria discussed re-staging scans with patient and all questions answered, patient is agreeable with the plan. Patient is aware that he should contact study team with any changes in status.  Pt will receive Week#19 treatment today with M7824, and will return to clinic on 04/07/20 for week #21 visit.
Week #19 Restaging

column2: On-study note; Treatment note; Week #1

On Study Note:  Day #1/Week 1  Patient accompanied by daughter, presented to clinic to complete screening and start treatment with  M7824 investigational drug product on 18C0056. Protocol eligibility checklist reviewed and verified by Dr. Strauss and Dr. Abdul-Sater and was deemed eligible to enroll on the clinical trial. Pt signed informed consent today and will receive first infusion today.  Dr. Morelli performed physical exam, reviewed medical history, to include current symptoms, and reconciled home medications. Please see progress note for her documented findings.   Dr. Adbul-Sater discussed the possible side effects of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent. He explained symptom management, to include when and how to call the treatment team and after hours coverage. They discussed the importance of reporting side effects promptly to the study team. Research nurse provided patient with study calendar of visits and important phone numbers for use to contact the study team. The patient and family member stated understanding of all information presented and all questions were answered. column2: On-study note; Treatment note; Week #3

Patient, accompanied by her daughter, presented to clinic for Week #3 of treatment on M7824; required research and routine labs collected per protocool. Pt is seen today by Dr. Pegna and staffed by Dr. Floudas. Dr. Floudas reviewed labs, adverse events, and patients current status. Any abnormal results not captured, are deemed not clincally significant.  Patient stated that she is feeling well overall. The first night, post infusion, patient  did note vaginal bleeding (upon wiping only), but has not had any other occurrences of bleeding after that time. Pt revealed that she has had vaginal bleeding in the past, and its presentation, quantity, and visual characteristics are not different from what she experienced in the past. Pt had infusion reaction with week 1 treatment, plan for infusion discussed with patient. Patient does not like taking benadryl, but after discussion with Dr. Floudas, is agreeable to taking PO benadryl with Famotodine, coupled with slower infusion rate. If tolerated well, will consider decreased PO dosing of benadryl at week 5.  Reinforced the importance of contacting the study team with any status changes and pt  confirmed that she has contact information for study team members. Pt stated understanding of all information presented.
All study medication(s) taken per protocol, M7824

column2: Treatment note; Week #3 HPV TRAP

Patient presented to clinic yesterday for Week # 3, of HPV TRAP study; routine and research labs were collected. The patient's physical examination, medication reconciliation, and adverse event assessment were performed by LTIB Nurse Practitioner Gloria Jackson;  her findings are documented in the patient's history & physical notes.  The patient had new complaints of frequent nausea and vomiting, onset around last Friday, some times 2-3 times per day.  She also complained about severe constipation, with her last bowel movement on 04/13/19.  She presented to the ED at home on 04/22/19,  prior to coming for her clinic visit; they performed a CT of the abdomen & pelvis.  She was not admitted, and was discharged.  She report being on antibiotics from her primary provider, started on 04/19/19, for a diagnosed UTI. Patient provided a copy of the CT scan imaging disc and report, both were sent to radiology for requested review by Dr. Strauss.  Dr. Strauss met with patient, reviewed her labs, and current status.  He advised patient that she would be admitted for supportive care and further work up of her symptoms.  He advised her of her elevated serum calcium and planned treatment for this.  The plan is for patient to have surgery consult, follow up with wound care, pain & palliative care, and psychiatry.  Dr. Strauss advised patient of his plan to possibly treat her with the study drug M7824, while she is inpatient. Patient was agreeable with this plan.
