column2: Treatment note; Week 43 Clinic visit

Patient presents accompanied by her husband for her Week #43 follow up visit; her M7824 study drug has been on hold due to central adrenal insufficiency; she continues on oral steroid treatment for this.  Her required labs and restaging CT scan were completed.  Dr. Hill reconciled the patient's concomitant medications; reviewed all prior and new adverse events; and performed the patient's physical assessment.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress noted.  Dr. Gatti-Mays met with patient, she reviewed the results of the restaging CT scan, which show patient continues to be stable based on her last scan. Patient has no new complaints at this time, continues to experience left ear fullness, which is residual from her last URI episode, from 02/21/19 visit.  Dr. Gatti-Mays suggested an ENT consult at her next visit.  All labs were within normal limits, and patient will continue at the prescribed dose of oral steroid for her adrenal insufficiency.  Her study drug M7824 hold will continue at this time; the patient will return in 2 weeks for follow up and possible ENT consult.  All adverse events reviewed and discussed with Dr. Gatti-Mays.

column2: Treatment note; Week 45 follow up

Patient presents accompanied by her husband for her Week #45 follow up visit; her M7824 study drug has been on hold due to central adrenal insufficiency; she continues on oral steroid treatment, hydrocortisone, for this.  Her required labs completed, Dr. Khan reconciled the patient's concomitant medications; reviewed all prior and new adverse events; and performed the patient's physical assessment.  Her findings are documented in the patient progress note.  Dr. Strauss met with patient, he reviewed her lab results for today, discussed adverse events and her current status. Patient has no new complaints at this time, with the warmer weather, she has been more active and is gardening.  All labs were within normal limits, and patient will continue at the prescribed dose of oral steroid for her adrenal insufficiency, 15 mg in the am and 5 mg  in the pm.  Her study drug M7824 hold will continue at this time. Dr Strauss advised patient that the protocol does allow for the lengthening of some required assessments for logistical reasons.  Since her M7824 hold continues, and her status has been stable; he advised patient that her next follow up visit can be in 4 weeks instead of 2 weeks.  Patient and her husband were agreeable with this.  Thus she will return to clinic in 4 week for restaging CT scan and clinic visit.  Research nurse confirmed that patient will still keep her Audiology and ENT consult visits for 04/09/19 and 04/10/19.  Patient advised to contact team if her status changes.  All adverse events reviewed and discussed with Dr. Strauss.

Reason for Visit:  Off-treatment note (18c0056 wk 193 & off treatment)
Protocol Documentation:  See prescriber note today for patient status details. AEs will be captured & recorded after review with PI for grades & attributions.

Patient has disease progression demonstrated on CT scan today per attending PI. Dr. Strauss discussed the different treatment options available to patient currently - STC chemotherapy with primary oncologist vs. different clinical trials. Patient states she does not intend to have any next chemotherapy and she would like to be screened for clinical trail, specifically study 20c0045. Dr. Strauss discussed study 20c0045 and answered all questions for patient and significant other. A copy of 20c0045 consent was emailed to patient at her request, to allow patient time to study consent & listed side effects.
Patient also states she has a scheduled appointment with her local urologist to discuss possible kidney ureteral stent placement and will keep study team informed of any future decisions.

Patient was enrolled onto 01c0129 screening protocol and agreeable to screen labs & ECG being collected today.  Patient will come off treatment for study 18c0056 due to disease progression determined by CT scan today.
Schedule and plan reviewed with patient, who verbalized understanding.

Patient aware of next appointment scheduled for 1 week from now, to potentially start on different treatment protocol.  Patient states she has study team contact information, should any new issues develop during interim.

column1: Last Updated: 07/24/2019 14:28 by Lamping, Elizabeth A (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,7/9/19,CC-CRIS,

column2: week 3

Patient seen in clinic on 7/23/19 for week 3 of 18c0056. Abnormal labs and symptoms noted but none clinically significant unless otherwise noted in physician-reviewed AEs.   Patient reported that she started having vaginal bleeding (intermittent baseline condition) 1 day after study drug infusion, increased dyspnea & hypoxia requiring 2L nasal cannula within the past week. She was found to have intermittent tachycardia to 130s, with significant lab abnormalities (anemia to 6.6, likely in s/o vaginal bleeding; new hyponatremia to 129; hypokalemia; hypomagnesemia) on clinical exam. Her energy level has been low, feeling fatigued, has been a little better with the oxygen but has not been eating much due to lack of appetite.   Patient was admitted to the hospital from clinic for vaginal bleeding and anemia.

Patient accompanied by his wife presented for week # 5 clinic and treatment on M7824; required labs were completed.  Dr. Clara reconciled home medications, assessed for adverse events, and performed the patient's physical exam.  His findings are documented in the patient's progress note.  Dr. Floudas met with patient, reviewed lab results, adverse events, and current status. The patient's labs results showed anemia and increasing liver enzyme results.   Dr. Floudas discussed these findings with the patient and his wife; advised that the M7824 dose for week #5 would be held because of this.  He reinforced that should patient  have increased dyspnea and fatigue more than he is experiencing now, he should contact his local oncologist to have labs drawn to repeat his complete blood count.  All other labs results are within normal limits, or if not addressed, are not clinically significant or are stable per baseline.  Research nurse gave patient supples for collection of an occult blood stool sample, if possible prior to him returning home tomorrow.  Also reinforced for patient to contact research team if his status changes.  Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for restaging scan and week # 7 clinic visit.  All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Floudas.
Missed doses..., Week # 5
Held for anemia and increasing  LFT's

column2: Adverse Event Summary Hospital Admit

Patient presented to local ED at home on 12/07/19, with worsening right upper quadrant abdominal pain.  CT scan in the ED showed right hepatic lesion intralesional bleed, and labs showed worsening anemia.  Patient was admitted on 12/08/19, for tumor hemorrhage requiring possible embolization and anemia requiring blood transfusions.  All AE's reviewed with Dr. Julius Strauss.

column2: week 7 18c0056

Patient seen in clinic for week 7 of 18c0056. Abnormal labs and symptoms noted but none clinically significant unless otherwise noted in physician-reviewed AE sheet. All AE's and attributions reviewed and approved by attending physician.  Patient states he is overall feeling better, although he continues to struggle with constipation and exertional dyspnea.   Physician reviewed restaging CT findings with patient and wife, which demonstrated disease progression. Physician explained that due to safety concerns for continued bleeding risk as well as radiographic disease progression, patient will be taken off treatment today. Future treatment options reviewed and discussed also.   Patient labs and exams from this visit will serve as end of treatment and also as 28 day safety follow up, as patient's last dose of study drug was on November 19,2019.   Patient and wife state they have study team contact information, should any new issues develop and patient is agreeable to continued telephone follow up per protocol at this time.

column2: Patient had week 25 labs drawn today; results were noted to have severe anemia. Patient was called by study team to return to NIH for treatment of anemia but patient declined to come right back. Patient states she has evening plans which she is unwilling to change at this time. Once impressed upon her how medically significant and dangerous this decision could be, patient has agreed to return to NIH after her dinner plans, at ~7:00pm. IN the meantime, patient agrees to go to nearest emergency room if she should become symptomatic prior to her arrival back at NIH.  Per Trish, the administrative coordinator, patient will be admitted to 3NE this evening when she returns. Information concerning patient was provided to charge RN on 3NE. MOS Hospitalist made aware of pending admission.  Patient was instructed to report to the Admissions office upon her arrival at NIH and they would direct her to the admitting unit.
Authored: Protocol Note

column2: week 33

Patient was unable to attend her week 33 scheduled protocol tests and clinic visit due to eruption of shingles at home this past two weeks. Patient informed study team that she was diagnosed at local urgent care on 1/10/19 and prescribed antiviral.  On 1/17-18/19 patient communicated that her blisters were pretty bad and her discomfort (pain, burning, oozing); she informed that she was prescribed steroids and prophylactic antibiotic, as well as the on-going antiviral.   After discussion with PI concerning patient's multiple previous episodes of AE Anemia (currently resolved), it was determined from review of results of endoscopy and colonoscopy that all previous episodes of anemia were POSSIBLY RELATED to hemorrhoids, stomach ulcer which most likely were present and on-going at baseline; UNLIKELY RELATED to IND/Research.

column1: Last Updated: 03/05/2020 10:36 by Lamping, Elizabeth A (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,6/12/18,CC-CRIS,

column2: On-study note; Treatment note; Week # 1

Patient has been deemed eligible for protocol 18C0056, he signed the inform consent document; and will receive his first week of M7824 treatment  today.  Eligibility checklist reviewed and verified by Dr. Strauss.  The calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance is 111 ml/min, based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine from 08/19/19.   Patient is inpatient, his most current assessment including medications are documented in the patient progress notes.   Dr. Strauss discussed the possible side effects and possible toxicities of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  He discussed and explained symptom management; including calling the treatment team or after hours covering provider to report side effects immediately at onset.  Research nurse provided patient with the important phone numbers to contact the research treatment team and after-hours solid tumor covering provider and page operator.  The patient was given the opportunity to ask questions, which were all addressed to his satisfaction.  A spanish interpreter, Rosa Garay, from Social Work, assisted with the informed consent process.  Patient will be given study calendar with future visit dates prior to his discharge.  He will receive week # 3, M7824 treatment in 2 weeks.
Authored: Protocol Note

column2: Treatment note; Day # 15

Patient presents for Day 15 treatment with NHS-IL12, required routine, research labs, and ECG were completed.  Dr. Pastor reconciled all home medications, assessed for adverse events, and performed the patients physical exam.  Her findings are documented in the patients progress note.  Dr. Gatti-Mays and the research nurse talked with patient on teleconference line.  Dr. Gatti-Mays reviewed the labs results, adverse events, and patients current status.  Patient reviewed the side effects she has to the drug, which had been documented in a prior telephone conversation with the research nurse.  She also noted having two nights of hot flashes on 3/19 and 3/20, which is unusual for her; she had general sweating, having to change her bed clothes on the 2 occasions.  All her symptoms have resolved.   Dr. Gatti-Mays discussed the lab results, stating we will monitor the mild increase in the patients liver enzymes at this time, but the increase is possibly related to the study drug.  She also discussed the urinalysis results; patient is asymptomatic  for urinary symptoms.  Dr. Gatti-Mays advised the changes in the urine may be related to her history of having a ureteral stent, which was placed due to her disease.  She encouraged patient to increase and keep herself well hydrated.   All lab results were addressed, abnormal labs will be monitored at this time.  Dr. Gatti-Mays approved the Day 15 NHS-IL12 injection.  The patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for restaging scan and decision if she will continue on this clinical trial if disease is stable or if she will switch to the HPV Trap study 18C0056.  Research nurse reinforced that patient should contact the study team if her status changes.   All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Gatti-Mays.

column1: Last Updated: 12/19/2018 16:19 by Francis, Deneise C (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,12/18/18,CC-CRIS,

column2: Week #1 Treatment follow up telephone calll

Research nurse spoke with patient, two days post her first infusion on the study, she states she tolerated the infusion well.  She states she has 3 items to discuss,  two of which she is trying to address with her local oncologist today:  Her history of right lower extremity lymphedema and  new right side/right rib cage area muscle spasms.  She also has new onset of pruritis to bilateral arms.  Right lower extremity lymphedema has be chronic since she developed her first DVT in 12/2016.  She has noticed within the last 4 months the swelling has increased.  Research nurse asked if patient wore compression hose while flying this week; she did not because she finds them uncomfortable.  She now has increased swelling and discomfort and just spoke with her local oncologist about coming in so they can assess her leg.  She states they did discuss ordering an Ultra Sound as part of this evaluation.  She states she is scheduled to meet the Lymphedema Therapist on 12/26/18.  She also reports a possible muscle strain, while standing and stretching on the flight back home yesterday, 12/19/18.  She started to experience intermittent muscle spasm to her right side and rib cage area, since returning home, and the duration has been frequent.  She just notified her oncologist office and they plan to call her back with a possible prescription of either pain medication or muscle relaxant.  She also reports new onset of itching to bilateral arms, from her wrist to her elbow; which started last night. The itching is intermittent, she denies pain, rash, or redness to her arms, denies chills or fever.  She had an episode last night and another this morning.  Research nurse advised patient to call her NIH treatment team if her status changes.  Advised her I will follow up with her next Monday, 12/24/18, to get an update on her status.
Authored: Protocol Note

column1: Last Updated: 12/20/2018 18:28 by Francis, Deneise C (RN)",Research Nurse Protocol - Note,C524417657,Research Note,C524417431,12/18/18,CC-CRIS,

column2: Treatment note; Week # 3

Patient presents for week of treatment; required labs were collected.  Dr. Monge Bonilla performed patient's physical exam, her findings are documented in the patient progress note.  All concomitant medications were reviewed and reconciled.   Patient states she tolerated her week 1 day 1 of treatment well, she did not experience any infusional reactions.   As documented in prior telephone contact note with the research nurse, she did experience a possible muscle strain when standing to stretch on her flight home 2 weeks ago (12/19/18), which caused intermittent muscle spasms.  She also experienced increased swelling to her right lower extremity starting the day after she returned home.  She visited her primary oncologist for both complaints. An ultrasound was performed at a local urgent care center, she was diagnosed with new deep vein thrombosis to the right lower extremity.  Her oncologist discontinued her Eliquis and started her on Lovenox, he also prescribed Baclofen for her muscle spasms.  Dr. Abdul Sater reviewed today's lab result, patient does have an elevated ALT.  Based on further inquiry by Dr. Monge Bonilla, patient admits she has been taking significant daily doses of Tylenol for right groin pain related to her new lower extremity DVT.  Dr. Adul Sater advised patient that based on this elevation in her ALT, the protocol guidance is for her week 3 treatment to be held today.  She has to immediately stop taking Tylenol for pain; she does have a follow up with her oncologist this Friday.  Dr. Adbul Sater will contact him about other pain control options due to elevated ALT. The plan is for her to repeat the liver function panel at home in one week to re-evaluate level.  She will return to clinic in 2 weeks for her scheduled visit and week 5 of treatment if her labs are within normal limits.
Authored: Protocol Note

column2: Treatment note; Day # 85

Patient accompanied by her daughter, presented for Day #85 of treatment with NHS-IL12 investigational drug product. Required routine and research labs, were completed. Dr. Gatti-Mays discussed the patients rising tumor marker, specifically her CA19-9; she discussed the possibility that the patient may have to start another clinical trial, due to possible disease progression. column2: Off-treatment note; Day 99

Patient accompanied by her daughter, presented for Day #99 of treatment with NHS-IL12 investigational drug product. Required routine and research labs, were completed. Dr. DeMaria performed the physical exam, reconciled home medications, and reviewed adverse events with patient.  His findings are documented in the patient progress note.  A spanish interpreter was not required for this visit.   Dr. Strauss and Dr. DeMaria reviewed the results of patient's most recent restaging scan. She does have disease progression and today will be her end of treatment visit for the NHS-IL12 clinical trial.  They discussed patient's decision to enroll on the 18C0056 clinical trial for HPV associated malignancies.   Her last injection on the study was 10/15/19; there are no required end of treatment labs or research labs per protocol calendar of events.  The last research labs were collected on 10/15/19, as part of her restaging visit.   The patient has no adverse events to report at this time.  She will return to clinic in one week for enrollment on 18C0056 to receive week #1 treatment.  The protocol requires a 30 day safety follow up visit based on the last dose which was 10/15/19; this can be done during her visit for the new study.   No adverse events to report for this visit, and all prior reported adverse events have resolved.

column2: On-study note; Week # 1

Patient accompanied by her daughter, presented for week # 1 of treatment with M7824 investigational drug product. Patient has been deemed eligible for protocol 18-C-0056, she signed the inform consent document, Spanish short form with a Social Work Spanish interpreter also acting as witness.   Protocol eligibility checklist reviewed and verified by Dr. Julius Strauss.  The calculated Cockcroft-Gault creatinine clearance is 96 ml/min, based on current height, weight, and serum creatinine from 10/15/19 screening labs.   Dr. Desai  performed her physical exam, reviewed medical history including current symptoms, and reconciled home medications. His findings are documented in the patient progress note.   Dr. Strauss discussed the possible side effects and possible toxicities of the investigational drug product as noted in the informed consent document.  He discussed and explained symptom management; including calling the treatment team or after hours covering provider to report side effects immediately at onset. The patient and family member were given the opportunity to ask questions, which were all addressed to their satisfaction.  All prior adverse events from prior clinical trial 11-C-0225 have all resolved, thus no new baseline symptoms or findings to report for he start of protocol 18-C-0056.

Dr. Sater discussed the results of her scan, which showed growth of a lymph node that  is not measurable, but was on a prior scan. He discussed restaging her in 4 week to evaluate the lymph node.  She continues to have symptoms associated with Adrenal Insufficiency (AI), which was diagnosed on 05/26/20 at an off scheduled visit. Per Dr. Abdul Sater's notes on 5/26/20, the AI is probably related to the M7824 study drug. These AI symptoms include; Fatigue, nausea/vomiting, myalgias, anorexia, weight loss, abdominal pain.  She was started on hydrocortisone 15 mg (10 mg in am and 5 mg in pm) daily for her AI on 05/26/20.   Her labs results  are within normal limits, any abnormalities, if not addressed are not clinically significant or are stable per baseline.  Based on current status and her AI symptoms Dr. Sater advised patient that her M7824 will be held today and possible subsequent visits, while her AI is controlled.    Research nurse reinforced to patient and her daughter to call the research team if her status changes.  Dr. Adams provided patient with a handout on AI and how to monitor her symptoms at home. She was also prescribed an emergency kit with hydrocortisone injection.  Patient will return to clinic in 2 weeks for week # 33 clinic visit.    All adverse events were reviewed with Dr. Abdul Sater.

column2: Patients daughter contacted with research nurse on Friday, 6/5/20, via text and telephone to advise that her mother may have had COVID-19 exposure.  The patient lives with her daughter and her daughters boyfriend who was recently diagnosed  COVID-19 positive last Tuesday, 6/2/20.  The patients daughter was in the process of trying to get herself tested.  She advised that her and her boyfriend were trying to self quarantine in their room and her Mom was self quarantined in her own room.  She advised that her Mom was fine, the only symptom her Mom reported was an cough.  Research nurse advised Dr. Strauss and Dr. Abdul Sater of the patients daughters contact and this new development.  They advised that with the risk of possible exposure, the patient should increase her Hydrocortisone dose from 15 mg daily to 30 mg daily. Reinforced that patient should monitor her symptoms and call the after hours on-call Fellow to report any change in her status.  Research nurse relayed this message to patients daughter.

column2: Treatment note; Week #33

All adverse events were reviewed by Dr. Strauss.

Protocol Documentation:  Patient presented to clinic, accompanied by her daughter for week #43 clinic and restaging scan; required scan and labs were completed.  Dr. Odeny reconciled home medications, assessed for adverse events, and performed the physical exam.  His findings are documented in the patient progress note.  The M7824 study drug hold continues due to diagnosis of Adrenal Insufficiency (AI) related to the drug.  Patient continues with Hydrocortisone treatment for AI.

Dr. Sater and research nurse met with Dr. Odeny and patient via virtual teleconference.  Dr. Sater reviewed the labs, CT scan results, adverse events, and patients current status.  He advised the patient and her daughter that there is disease progression on her scans; he discussed the next steps in her treatment, including enrollment on protocol 20-C-0045.  The patient reports that since the beginning of the month, she has noticed the smell of cigarette smoke around her; but no one in her home smokes and smoking is not allowed at her job.  Dr. Sater and Dr. Odeny discussed that this change in smell may be residual changed from her prior COVID-19 infection.  Her labs results show elevated TSH; which prompted Dr. Sater to increase her dose of Synthyroid; patient states she has being taking the drug as prescribed and has not missed any doses. Patient also confirmed she is taking her Hydrocortisone medication as prescribed.   She denies any symptoms related to the elevated TSH, her other lab results are within normal limits.  Patient and her daughter will review the consent for 20-C-0045 and call research nurse with their decision; with plan to start treatment in 2 weeks.  Research nurse reinforced that patient should contact research team if her status changes.
Dr. Houssein Abdul Sater reviewed all adverse events.
